\begin_layout Subsection
Features of olfactory stimuli 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An odor stimulus consists of one or more voltalized chemicals (or odorants)
 that is typically of low molecular weight (< 300 Da 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Riffell:2016ce"

\end_inset

) transported from a source through the air to the olfactory organ.
 Since odor stimuli, unlike light or sound stimuli, consists of physical
 movement of molcules, the dominant feature of an odor stimulus is the the
 identity of the molecules percieved.
 The number of unique odorants is very large, and different molecules are
 produced by different sources, have different valence, are percieved by
 different insects.
 However, the fact that all these molucles have to be transported by the
 air and have to be detected by insects means that many olfactory stimuli
 share commonalities regardless of their chemical compositions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Physics of the odor environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All olfactory stimuli begin by odorant molecules evaporating from some source.
 These voltalized molecules move with the air that surrounds them, and their
 temporal evolution and statistics depends therefore on the movement of
 the air that they are carried by.
 Two non-dimensional numbers, the Péclet number and the Reynolds number,
 are useful descriptors of moving airstreams and thus can determine the
 statistics of the odor signals within them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Péclet number is defined as the ratio of the advective and diffusive
 transport rates of a species in a flow.
 These two rates are determined by the ambient motion of the air and molecular
 diffusion that occurs by Brownian motion.
 For most insects navigate airborne odor stimuli, these two processes occur
 at very different scales: diffusion is slow and local, and advection is
 fast and extensive.
 Thus, Péclet number are typically large and odorant motion is dominated
 by advection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Riffell:2008hp"

\end_inset

.
 This means that the motion of the air cannot be neglected when considering
 odor signals, and that in many cases, fluctuations in odor signals are
 correlated with fluctuations in instantenous flows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Reynolds number is the ratio of the intertial forces to viscous forces
 within a fluid.
 It can be used to predict the transition from laminar to turbulent flow,
 and since the temporal statistics of odor signals are expected to be very
 different in the two cases, the Reynolds number is an important determinant
 of the olfactory environment.
 Insects navigating to an odor source in large Reynolds nuymber environments
 will experience intermittent, filamentous odor stimuli, while insects navigatin
g low Reynolds environments will experience door signals that can resemble
 more smooth gradients 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Riffell:2008hp"

\end_inset

, which can occur during periods of still air.
 
\end_layout

