\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fruit fly, 
\emph on
Drosophila melanogaster
\emph default
, has been the system of choice for many studies on insect olfaction.
 The focus on 
\emph on
Drosophila 
\emph default
stems from several reasons: (i) it is easy to grow and maintain in laboratories,
 with a short generation time; (ii) its genome has been sequenced, and a
 large variety of genetic tools are available for 
\emph on
Drosophila
\emph default
; (iii) its olfactory system is similar to other insects, and even to vertebrate
s in gross organisation, though numerically simpler.
 While the anatomy of Drosophila is described in the following section,
 many features are common to the olfactroy system of other insects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary olfactory organs in Drosophila are the antennae and the maxillary
 palps.
 The antennae are not just olfactory organs but are also organs of audition
 and mechanosensation.
 The olfactroy functions of the antennae are localized to its third segment,
 which are covered in fine sensory hairs called sensilla.
 Sensilla are also present on the maxillary palp.
 Based on their morphology, sensilla can be divided into three types: basiconic
 (10 functional types), coeloconic (4 types) and trichoid (4 types).
 Based on identified ligans, basiconic sensilla largely respond to voltaile
 food odors; coeloconic sensilla largely redpong to amines, humidity and
 a few food odors; and trichoid sensilla respond to volatile compounds and
 pheromones from other flies, like cis-vaccenyl acetate.
 The antenna has all three types of sensilla, that exhibit some degree of
 grouping on the surface, while the maxilalry palp only has basiconic sensilla.
 The structural and functional organisation of sensilla into these groups
 is similar in other insects (de Bruyne and Baker 2008).
 
\end_layout

